segments.text: Good morning, everyone.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Thank you for being here.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I'm Tammy Morales, Seattle City Councilmember representing District 2, CID, down to Rainier Beach.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I also serve as the Vice Chair for the Seattle-King County Board of Health.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I want to thank you all for joining us this very early morning.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: We're joined today by several community partners from Legal Voice, Planned Parenthood, and Pro-Choice Washington, as well as my colleague, Councilmember Lisa Herbold, and I want to thank everybody for being here.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I'm going to make my remarks, but first I do want to introduce the other speakers who are going to be here today.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: We have Kim Clark, who is legal director for Reproductive Rights, Health, and Justice at Legal Voice, a nonprofit organization that advances gender equity throughout the Pacific Northwest through impact litigation, policy advocacy, and legal rights education.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Ms.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Clark's work includes cases in federal and state court throughout the Pacific Northwest that seek to protect and expand rights of all people to reproductive justice.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Ms.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Clark also manages an extensive portfolio of policy initiatives in both Washington and Idaho.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Ms.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Clark holds a JD from Harvard Law School and a BA from the University of Arizona.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Next, we'll be hearing from Kia Guarino, the Executive Director of ProChoice Washington, which is the lead organization dedicated to political and legislative advocacy for reproductive freedom in Washington State.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Kia brings a background in global health and international development, having worked with gender and health equity advocates in communities across the world, with the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, Albright Stonebridge Group, the Clinton Foundation, Operation Smile, and Amnesty International.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: She also earned her Master's in International Economics and a Master's in International Health from Johns Hopkins University.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Next, we have Yvette Maguña, who serves as the Washington Government Relations Manager at Planned Parenthood Alliance Advocates.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Yvette previously worked with One America and Fuse Washington and brings her background as a community organizer into the work she does to fight for reproductive justice, economic justice, and immigrant rights.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: And we will be hearing from my colleague, Lisa Herbold, representing District 1.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Councilmember Herbold is also on the King County Board of Health with me.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: And our offices have been working together on this legislation that I'm very glad to be co-sponsoring with her.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: So that's our lineup for today, and we'll just pass it off to one another.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: So we're here today after weeks of onslaught and attacks on human rights from our U.S.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Supreme Court.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I know the past months have been particularly heavy for many across the country.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: On June 24th, the Supreme Court disregarded 50 years of precedence and achieved their agenda to take away a person's right to choose by forcing people to give birth against their will, by violating human and constitutional rights.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: While this decision has led to unspeakable sorrow, fury, and anxiety, we must not let it lead to despair.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: One in four women in this country has had an abortion, including me.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I'm terrified and outraged that for many people who will need abortion care today and every day forthcoming, and particularly for black and brown folks across this country, their protection and their privacy is in jeopardy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Make no mistake, this ruling by the Supreme Court is mandating forced pregnancy and taking away the right to self-determination and personal freedom.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: While we in Seattle and Washington have the secure right to abortion, too many across the country do not.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: From a municipal standpoint, I'm focusing on protections that we can put in place to extend care to the people who will be crossing state lines to seek the care they deserve in our city.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Our office has been working on legislation since the Supreme Court's draft opinion was leaked, and there's two pieces of legislation that will be coming up in my committee tomorrow.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: The first is Council Bill 120374.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: It's an ordinance that would guarantee civil rights protections for those who have received or are seeking abortions.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: With the increase in expected travel to the City of Seattle,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: For those who are seeking abortion care, there will be lots of wraparound services including hotel and meals provided by businesses.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: So this legislation would ensure that people who are seeking abortion are protected at every step along the way and cannot be discriminated against.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: It's also important to note that these protections will apply regardless of one's documentation status and in concurrence with many of our other city regulations.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: The second piece of legislation is Council Bill 120376.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: It would create a misdemeanor charge for people who encroach on individuals seeking abortion care or gender affirming care by physically blocking access to a healthcare facility where these services are provided.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Examples of this include physically obstructing access to a healthcare facility where services are provided.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Wait, I just said that.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Sorry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Or impeding the passage of people seeking to enter or depart from a facility, making noise that unreasonably disrupts the people within the facility, or threatening to inflict injury on the people or employees of the facility.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: This legislation adopts RCW 9A-50-020 around interference at healthcare facilities into the Seattle Criminal Code.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: In essence, it would allow the city attorney's office to prosecute a misdemeanor in Seattle Municipal Court, and this protection would extend to those who are visiting facilities to access gender-affirming care, such as surgery or hormones.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: These two bills are just the beginning of protections that we have working in the city.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I will say we're also working on legislation that would regulate crisis pregnancy centers in Seattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Crisis pregnancy centers are typically conservative Christian organizations that work to persuade pregnant people against having abortions.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: They often appear to operate as abortion clinics that provide emergency contraception or referral to those services, but they do not actually provide that information once a patient enters, instead redirecting them to adoption or other alternatives.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: And our legislation would work to ensure that these facilities cannot make public statements that are false or misleading by creating penalties for engaging in this kind of information.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: We're modeling this legislation from other jurisdictions, specifically the San Francisco ordinance, where they've been successful in upholding this ordinance.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Also, my office is leveraging every resource available to protect abortion services for those who need it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I want to thank Council Member Herbold for her continued partnership on this critical work, as well as all of the healthcare workers, service providers, and advocates who have been doing this important, life-saving work.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I also want to name my appreciation for both Mayor Harrell and for King County Executive Constantine, both of whom have put forth commitments from the municipal and the county level to contribute to abortion funds in the Northwest.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I know this is just a start and that reproductive justice organizers have been anticipating these rollbacks for decades.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: But what gives me hope in these times is knowing that across the country, there are robust support systems that have been in place to support access to abortion care and reproductive health care for years.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: As electeds, we must come together to organize and ensure that everyone's fundamental right to privacy and the right to decide what to do with their own bodies is protected.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I'm proud to stand firm alongside my colleagues and community advocates today and declare that Seattle is a city where we strengthen existing protections and we create systems of support for people who are seeking abortion care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: The fight for reproductive justice will continue and I will be supporting these fights at every level that I can.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Thank you all for being here today and I am going to pass it to Kim Clark.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Thank you.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Thank you so much, Councilmember Morales.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Again, my name is Kim Clark, and I'm the Legal Director at Legal Voice, which has been working to advance gender equity throughout the Pacific Northwest for over 40 years.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: As Councilmember Morales said, make no mistake, the decision in Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization is an unprecedented attack.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: by the highest court in the land on the fundamental rights of people who can become pregnant, which will profoundly impact other areas of the law as well.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: That the court did so without so much as acknowledging the impacts that its decision would have on the real lives of people who can become pregnant, especially the most marginalized, speaks volumes.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Thankfully, abortion remains legal in Washington regardless of this deeply flawed decision.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But that doesn't mean that the decision won't impact Washington.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: In fact, the Guttmacher Institute estimates that there will be an increase, a 385% increase, in people who rely on Washington providers for abortion care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: While Washington welcomes all those in need, without a significant infusion of resources, this massive influx of patients into our state will constrain access even here.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We also know that anti-abortion states won't stop at banning abortion within their borders, but will try every way possible to punish out-of-state providers for offering assistance to those in need of abortions, and even punishing pregnant people themselves.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: At the very least, we need protections, legal protections, to ensure that the state of Washington won't cooperate in those state attacks, which lawmakers at the state level are working to develop.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But in the meantime, the anti-abortion movement is feeling emboldened.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: That means that we can expect even more attacks on the rights of people who can become pregnant and other communities as well, especially those who stand at the intersection of multiple forms of oppression.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: by actors such as private employers, health care providers, and other places of public accommodation.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: That's why the anti-discrimination protections that Councilmember Morales spoke of are so important.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We've also seen already a drastic uptick in threatening and harassing protest activity outside of reproductive health clinics throughout our states, which we know will only get worse.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Intimidation and harassment of patients and providers has long been a strategy of the anti-abortion movement, especially in states like Washington.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: In fact, because it's one of the only strategies that works for them here.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Increasingly, that strategy of intimidating and harassing patients and providers includes
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: digital surveillance.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And while the risks to patient privacy are numerous, there is none more concerning than the vast network of fake clinics the anti-abortion movement has built throughout the country to surveil pregnant people and to prevent them from accessing abortion and contraception.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And of course I'm talking about crisis pregnancy centers, which are fake clinics that outnumber real reproductive health clinics by three to one in the United States, including in the state of Washington.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And these clinics exist to spread misinformation and prevent pregnant people from accessing abortion care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But they also serve another purpose that people are less aware of, and that's to collect
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: vast amounts of personal health information that can now be used to support civil and criminal cases against pregnant people and their providers.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And that's because the majority of crisis pregnancy centers not only spread misinformation, they actually provide no medical services whatsoever.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: They may provide drugstore pregnancy tests and
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: keepsake ultrasounds, which are exactly what they sound like, basically a souvenir.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But the people operating those ultrasound machines often don't have the skills to read the results, much less diagnose pregnancy complications.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But what this means is that most crisis pregnancy centers are not subject to HIPAA or any other privacy protections, which means that they can use the personal health information that they're collecting
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: from unsuspecting patients, basically however they see fit.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Again, this is another reason why it's so important to regulate the activities of crisis pregnancy centers and that we be aware of what they are.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Fortunately, advocates and providers in Washington stand ready to meet these challenges
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: with the support of strong leaders at all levels of government.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: The Supreme Court in Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization is on the wrong side of history.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But make no mistake, we here in Washington and in Seattle in particular will continue to fight until all people truly enjoy true reproductive justice.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Thank you.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Good morning.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: My name is Kia Guarino again, and I'm the Executive Director of Pro-Choice Washington, which is the leading grassroots advocacy organization in Washington State that has been working to promote and protect reproductive freedom for every single person for nearly 50 years.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: I want to thank Councilmember Herbold and Councilmember Morales for your leadership, as well as the other leaders across Washington State who are standing up
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: for the protection of these critical rights.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: I also want to acknowledge the hard work of my fellow community activists who have, for decades, been working to prepare for this moment, which is why we are, in Seattle and Washington, able to meet this moment through important legislation and through activism.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: So this legislation, along with continued local investments in reproductive abortion funds, like the Northwest Abortion Access Fund, as well as reproductive clinics, is really essential to meet this moment.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: And you've heard my colleague speak about the unprecedented expectations of patient needs, both across Washington and across the country, that we in Seattle specifically, but across Washington, will need to meet.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: So we need to make additional investments to prepare.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: We also know that this moment is not necessarily going to stay the same for Washington, that we have a lot of work to do as activists, as individuals, to continue to protect our rights here.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: And that means that we all have a responsibility to continue to work to protect both quality care and to counter the stigma that has allowed us to get here.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: So all of us have a responsibility to be able to speak a little bit more clearly about abortion rights as fundamental
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: health care rights, as fundamental human rights, as fundamental civil rights, and as a critical component of socioeconomic advancement for all people.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: Even here in Washington, we know that abortion access is protected, but it is not equally protected for every single person, and that includes discriminatory restrictions within our health care system.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: So along with these investments, along with this important legislation,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: we need to continue to work to counter other discriminatory biases within our health care system, including the restriction of care across hospitals in Washington state.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: So over the last decade, we have seen a 26% increase in hospital beds being subject to discriminatory restrictions in the policies within those hospitals.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: And this results in a refusal of care for reproductive care, for gender-affirming care, and other important basic health care rights in Washington.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: So when we consider the influx of patients that will be arriving, we need to recognize that there are restrictions across our health system that still need to be addressed.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: We still need to look at those health systems and we still need to hold our own systems accountable for the rights that they are denying.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: As you've also heard several times, crisis pregnancy centers are essential to address.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: They are denying quality care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: They are putting people in medical risk by either providing misinformation
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: or refusing to provide accurate information, and they are also putting patients at significant risk through the privacy, the data privacy issues that Kim so clearly articulated for us.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: And this is a moment where we all need to come together, we all need to recognize that
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: This is the first very important step, and we are deeply privileged to be in a place that still has room for steps, but that there is a lot of work that we all have to do as individuals to continue to counter the stigma, to continue to counter medical discrimination, and to continue to push for funding for our abortion funds and our clinics.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: So thank you very much, and I will pass it now to Yvette.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: Thank you, Kia.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: And thank you, Council Members Morales and Council Member Herbold, for your ongoing leadership in protecting and advancing abortion access in Seattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: We are grateful to have you as allies and champions on this critical care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: My name is Yvette Magana, and I'm the Washington Government Relations Manager at Planned Parenthood Alliance Advocates.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: It's been almost a month since the Supreme Court overturned nearly 50 years of precedent and eliminated the fundamental right to abortion.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: In that time, my colleagues at Planned Parenthood and abortion providers around the country have seen patients who are scared, unsure of where to turn, and being stripped of the right to this fundamental basic healthcare.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: In Washington State, thanks to decades of relentless work to defend and expand our rights by leaders here in Seattle and across the state, abortion is still legal.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: Abortion providers here in Washington are and will remain open to all patients.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: But we're not just here for Washington patients.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: We're here for everyone, no matter what state you live in, no matter who your lawmakers and governor are, providers in Washington are here to welcome you with open arms.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: We are already seeing patients from states across the country whose own lawmakers have abandoned them and left them without access to basic health care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: It's because of strong support and unwavering commitment of leaders like Councilmember Morales and Councilmember Herbold that we expect, as Kim Clark stated earlier, an influx of patients in the coming months and years.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: Studies estimate that we expect a 385% growth in out-of-state patients traveling to Washington to access abortion care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: That's why policies announced today are so critical to safeguarding and maintaining abortion access in Seattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: We want our providers and patients to be safe, protected, and empowered to continue to provide abortion throughout the county and the entire state, no matter what.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: And let's be clear, we know not all patients who want to travel to Washington to access abortion will be able to get here for care.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: The state abortion bans sweeping the country are disproportionately feeling Black, Latino, Indigenous, and other people of color, people with low incomes, LGBTQ people, people with disabilities, immigrants, and more due to this country's legacy of racism and systemic oppression.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: Abortion is healthcare, period.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: We are grateful for the leaders here today and across the state for standing strong and ensuring patients can rely on Washington State for healthcare.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: Thank you again to Councilmembers Morales and Herbold for being a strong voice for our providers, patients, and our reproductive healthcare community.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: We look forward to working in partnership with you and I'll now hand it to Councilmember Herbold.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_05

segments.text: Thank you, Yvette.

segments.text: Thank you, Kim.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: Thank you, Kia.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02
